Ife Ogunfuwa Bayelsa, Ebonyi and Ekiti states have recorded the least number of active voice and Internet subscriptions on Global System for Mobile communication in the country in the first six months of the year. The latest report from the National Bureau of Statistics indicated that Bayelsa State’s voice subscriptions in the first quarter were 1.20 million and 1.26 million in the second quarter. It recorded 889,358 and 925,460 Internet subscriptions in first quarter and second quarter of 2019, respectively. The data showed that Ebonyi State had 1.58 million and 1.63 million voice subscriptions in Q1 and Q2, respectively. It recorded 1.06 million and 1.1 million Internet subscriptions in the corresponding period. In Ekiti State, 1.62 million and 1.63 million voice subscriptions were reported in Q1 and Q2 respectively. It had 1.19 million and1.24 million Internet subscriptions in Q1 and Q2, respectively. Lagos, Ogun and Kano states recorded the highest number of active voice and Internet subscriptions from the mobile network operators in the country in the first and second quarters of 2019. According to the data, active voice subscriptions in Lagos State hit 23.1 million in Q1 and dropped to 22.61 million in Q2. The state recorded 15.89 million Internet subscriptions in Q1 and 16.48 million in Q2 of 2019. The NBS statistics revealed that in Ogun State, 10.24 million active voice subscriptions were recorded in Q1 and 10.37 million in Q2. Its Internet subscriptions were given as 7.11 million in Q1 and 7.45 million in Q2. In Kano State, the industry data indicated that its 9.74 million voice subscriptions in Q1 rose to 10.07 million in Q2 while Internet subscriptions increased from 6.26 million in Q1 to 6.85 million in the second quarter of this year. The NBS data showed that the number of subscribers that returned to their mobile network operator through the mobile number portability platform increased by 25 per cent quarter-on-quarter. Analyses of the mobile portability statistics showed that incoming porting activities in the first quarter of 2019 were 24,063 while in the second quarter, a total of 30,168 subscribers moved back to their original service provider. The data indicated that 9mobile had the highest porting activities in the two quarters, having recorded the highest incoming porting in Q1(13,314) and Q2 (19,369). However, the outgoing porting data showed that in the first quarter of 2019, a total of 22,666 subscribers left their original network operators to new operators. In the second quarter, 20,133 mobile phone users moved to other networks, amounting to 11 per cent decline in outgoing porting activities quarter-on-quarter. Incoming porting refers to the number of subscribers that left another service provider’s network into their original service provider’s network. Outgoing porting shows the number of subscribers that left their original service providers to other network providers. Copyright PUNCH.
